<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="409" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,444,1620,1646]" box="[151,444,1620,1646]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,444,1620,1646]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,444,1620,1646]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409">
<taxonomicName box="[151,270,1620,1646]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Chelostoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapunculi">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,270,1620,1646]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="409">rapunculi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1690,1931]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409">
Preoccipital ridge raised to a carina. Basal zone of propodeum distinctly sloping and usually only about half as long as metanotum. Anterior surface of tergum 
<number box="[630,644,1727,1751]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" value="1.0">1</number>
shallowly concave. Females: Clypeus only slightly protruding or with flat narrow apical zone (
<figureCitation box="[428,498,1762,1787]" captionStart="FIGURE 5 – 10. 5" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1350,1372]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1328]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[153,1433,193,1329]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 5 – 10. 5: Chelostoma clypeale, head of female. 6: Chelostoma clypeale: terga 4 – 7 of male. 7: Chelostoma clypeale, sterna 2 – 4 of male. 8: Chelostoma tonsum, head of male. 9: Chelostoma tonsum, terga 4 – 7 of male. 10: Chelostoma tonsum, sterna 2 – 3 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238288/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="409">
Fig. 
<number box="[482,498,1762,1787]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Males: Median elevation on sternum 
<number box="[944,958,1763,1787]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" value="2.0">2</number>
of uniform shape among species, roughly triangular in lateral view, its posterior surface evenly sloping, of half-elliptical shape and almost flat (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1423,1798,1823]" captionStart="FIGURE 11 – 19. 11" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1885,1907]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,375,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,375,1863]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 11 – 19. 11: Chelostoma orientale, head of female. 12: Chelostoma orientale, sternum 2 of male. 13: Chelostoma orientale, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 14: Chelostoma handlirschi, head of female. 15: Chelostoma handlirschi, sternum 2 of male. 16: Chelostoma aegaeicum, sternum 2 of male. 17: Chelostoma nasutum, head of female. 18: Chelostoma nasutum, sternum 2 of male. 19: Chelostoma hebraeum, sternum 2 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238289/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="409">
Fig. 
<number box="[1392,1423,1799,1823]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
). Apical zone of sternum 
<number box="[432,446,1835,1859]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" value="4.0">4</number>
without dense pilosity of yellowish hairs. Tergum 
<number box="[1039,1053,1835,1858]" pageId="1" pageNumber="409" value="7.0">7</number>
tripartite with one lower median tooth and two upper lateral teeth (
<figureCitation box="[545,647,1870,1895]" captionStart="FIGURE 5 – 10. 5" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1350,1372]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1328]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[153,1433,193,1329]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 5 – 10. 5: Chelostoma clypeale, head of female. 6: Chelostoma clypeale: terga 4 – 7 of male. 7: Chelostoma clypeale, sterna 2 – 4 of male. 8: Chelostoma tonsum, head of male. 9: Chelostoma tonsum, terga 4 – 7 of male. 10: Chelostoma tonsum, sterna 2 – 3 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238288/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="409">Fig. 6, 9</figureCitation>
), which are rarely fused to a straight uninterrupted transverse apical margin.
</paragraph>
